They recommend additional services based on the mileage/fluid levels, but in a professional way. You can always say no. The best part I think is 100% transparency. They actually show you all the parts before/after replacing, which never happens in other places I have been to(and you can actually see them removing/installing the parts because you are sitting in the car). I will definitely go back next time! The only downside is the wait time depending on the line. I luckily had only one car in front of me and it took about 1.5hrs in total. I think the line moves at a pace of about ~45min~1hr per car.</Review>

< Review>
It was my first time going here today for an oil change. Everyone was very friendly and I was immediately greeted and told there was going to be a 45 minute to an hour wait (it ended up being much less than that). Was given free water and coffee, which actually wasn't half bad. During the service they did try to upsell products but it's a business so I understand. Just politely decline and move on. If you let them know you had your fluids serviced at another shop recently they can code that into the system. With the 10 dollar yelp coupon my total came out to $45.68 after tax and waste disposal fee ($3.00). Very reasonable price considering if I were to buy everything myself it would come out to $35 to $40 not including the time it would take me to do it and the fact that I would have to deal with disposing the old oil. Thanks to Jovonne, Victor, and Franklin for the pleasant experience. I'll definitely be recommending this place.< /Review>

<rating>5< /rating><Review>I really like this place; the menu exactly hits the spot for anyone looking for a great lunch spot with modest prices and has a variety of flavor palettes.

In one meal I had an Italian item and an Asian item; both were executed flavorfully (not bland) and thoughtfully (the flavors were exciting and authentic).

Not only that, but there are many different platforms for the flavors, whether by bowl, bun, wrap, or noodle.

Importantly, the portion sizes were satisfying!

Finally customer service and speed is good. I don't know if it's their preferred method, but if you're not able to call, they also take orders by email. Useful for detailed orders or during a work meeting!< /Review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< resp>

< review>
Hands down the best food in Ontario. I used to work in the area from 2014 to 2016 tried everything around here. The wait can be long during the busy lunch hour, but it is worth waiting for (or taking your lunch a little later to avoid the crowd). I came back to try it out today (August 2018) and everything was just as good as I remembered. Same friendly owner and same great food. I'm definitely coming back here next time I'm in town.< /review>

Delicious with their branded hot-sauce.As for the spicy pork plate, it is served over white steamed rice, along with a slice of watermelon. The pork is very tender, spicy and minimal diced onion</review>

Do not go here!<//text><name>Emyly Hall< /name><pictures>None</pictures><Resp>{'time': 1520363495495, 'text': "Hi Emyly,\n\nI apologize for the delay in getting your itemized receipt and I hope the following can shed some light on the insurance and co-pay issue.\n\nMedical insurance and billing, is a pain for everyone. Here are three important things you need to know:\n\n1. It‚Äôs important to know that we always process an insurance benefit check prior to patients coming in or sometimes when they arrive if we do not have their insurance information ahead of time. We discuss their insurance deductible and costs with them and never order anything or charge anything unless it is authorized by the patient.\n\n2. We collect an amount that we are told, to the penny, by each patient's insurance company. This is usually calculated by them based on how much has been credited to their annual deductible plus the terms of their individual insurance plan. That number is usually right, but not always, depending on when other bills come in before ours to the insurance company.  But if there are any discrepancies we always refund the difference.\n\n3. We do not bill insurance companies and collect the balance later from patients due to the proliferation of high deductible plans and to avoid having to chase patients down for payment thus we try hard to be totally upfront about costs so they do not get a surprise bill.\n\nIf you still need a copy of your receipt or have any other questions, please feel free to contact me at webhelp@footankleinstitute.com\n\nLastly, in regard to the ‚Äú10-minute appointment,‚Äù our doctors spend the amount of time needed with each individual patient. In your case, it is very possible that your issues were easy enough that only 10 minutes was needed.  Simpler cases result in shorter appointments while more complex cases require more time.\n\nYes, some answers may be found on WebMD as sometimes things are easy. But if it was a more serious issue than you thought it was, you would have been darn happy to have learned about it. 118227898680955427051<//user>
<name>Andrei Muresianu< /name><date>1532236207475<//date><Rate>5<//Rate>< text>
I have horrible feet. Bad DNA. My aunt and my mother have both had multiple surgeries. I had hallux rigidis in both feet and neuromas in both feet.

I met with surgeons at Cedars, Kerlan Jobe, UCLA, DISC, and other places. Then I asked my primary care physician (with St. John's which has Santa Monica Orthopedic Group / SMOG) who he would pick and he said his daughter is having bunion surgery and he is going to Dr. Baravarian. My brother in law and a high school friend who are both orthopedic surgeons most-agreed with Dr. Baravarian's diagnosis and treatment advice. It is a luxury in LA to have many good surgeons to choose from but I have now had three surgeries with Dr. Baravarian and am 100% happy I chose to go with University Foot and Ankle.

Quick rundown:
Playing sports means more to me than almost anything.
I am in the gym playing basketball, out playing tennis, skiing, running with my dog, or at least lifting weights 6-7 days a week, 52 weeks a year. I'm 6'3" and 200lbs so I am tough on my feet. When I play basketball I play in a game with a number of people who used to play professionally in Europe and the NBA. It is a high level game and it was very important to me that after foot surgery I wasn't just going to be "walking pain free" again but playing at the highest level I could.

Neuromas in both feet were handled wonderfully. I was suffering from a lot of irritation. The bottoms of my feet had pockets of fluid where my body was trying to protect myself from the rubbing on the nerve and anything athletic was painful. The feet were swollen slightly afterwards but I basically was walking right away. Over time the feet were a bit sore and it took a little while to heal but after a few months I could not tell the surgeries were ever done. Perfect.

In my left foot I had a cheilectomy for the hallux rigidis. 6 years after the surgery it feels great. One day I may need to go to a full fusion here but not yet. The cheilectomy felt easy. It was a while ago but I think I was walking that day. It healed great.

In my right foot I had a cheilectomy done knowing that eventually I might have to have a full fusion because that foot was in much worse shape than my left foot. 6 years later I had the fusion done (March of 2018). By the end of June I was playing tennis again, playing basketball, running and squatting in the gym. I can explode off my right foot (my plant foot) and get above the rim in basketball with ZERO felt difference between my toe pre and post-fusion. Actually post-fusion it only feels better because it is pain free (and range of motion is indistinguishable).

If I had any regret at all it is that I didn't get both toes fused just because the fusion went SO WELL on the right foot that why not take the risk of ever having to get the left foot cheilectomy redone off the table for the rest of my life?

So that is it - I have had numerous surgeries with Dr. Baravarian. He consistently recommended a thoughtful and conservative treatment approach, every single surgery has led to a great outcome I am very happy with, his office is always accommodating if I need to get in for something small like a new pair of orthotics or something more important like seeing Dr. Baravarian about new foot pain. As a surgeon, Dr. Baravarian listened to my athletic goals and customized the plate that fixed my fusion in place. Also Dr. Baravarian listened to my reasonable concerns about wanting to travel for work and not wanting to be in a cast for 3 straight months, switching me to a boot after a reasonable period of time. This let me start walking earlier, didn't atrophy my muscles as much, was able to stay more connected at work and was psychologically relieving. Other surgeons were more conservative about keeping you in a cast forever. I appreciate a surgeon who is willing to listen to the patient and be reasonable and thoughtful based on the individual.

10 stars.< /text>
<pics>None</pics>< Response>

<Gmap_id>0x80dc01c79c654487:0xbb6fa8346f72d9ea< /Gmap_id>< text>
When I think to the time I lived in Pacific Beach, one of the best memories I have is of my frequent stops at Better Buzz Coffee. Whether you're on the way to work, or to the beach for a walk on the boardwalk, Better Buzz is the perfect way to start your day. I recommend their "Best Drink Ever" but half sweet - otherwise it's a little too sugary. Their acai bowls are also a must have. The classic espresso drinks are also great quality - smooth and rich in flavor.</text>

The place is small but very popular. They have a wide variety of coffees and even offer tea. The flavored coffee is a little on the sweet side, but they offer to make it half sweet or less sweet when asked. There's parking at the site that shares it with the Jack in the Box. The drive thru usually has a line, so beware. The staff is sweet and they have a cute thing with Harry Potter at the mall.</Review>

< review>
So I would give this place a 5 star review only if I actually liked really sugary coffee drinks. My girlfriend suggested this place on our way out of San Diego, so we stopped by. The drive thru had a line into the street, which is a good thing, obviously people love this place. The menu had a long list of different types of coffee drinks to pick from along with juices and blended drinks too.

I ordered the popular drink, I believe it was "the famous coffee" or something along that line. Overall very tasty but once again  it's overkill on the sweetness for me. They did have an option to go half sweetness, so next time I will be trying that and updating my review from there. Starbucks lovers are in for a treat going here!<//review>

< Review>
If I'd reviewed this place after the first couple visits, I'd have given them 5 stars. Unfortunately, because we (my wife and I) were so impressed, we visited them a number of times over a couple week time period. I'm not sure what happened because they were initially great but over those two weeks they descended to below average. Initially they got all our orders correct the first time, and the drinks were delicious (we have blended mochas, hot mochas, and even the smoothies); but our last several visits have been marred. They've gotten our order incorrect multiple times--in spite of our attempts to ensure they get it down right by repeating it multiple times for clarity--and then, most recently, they burned the espresso (yuck!) when remaking the drink they made incorrectly (I asked for an almond milk mocha--not a coconut milk mocha). In short, they went from well worth the long wait in the drive thru and the prices they charge to completely forgettable and not worth going out of our way for. At this point, given my experiences with Better Buzz on Garnet Avenue, I'd say your chances of getting stellar espresso here aren't any better than they are at any other coffee shop.<//Review>

< text>
Delivery girl worked a $10 tip out of me.  It  was Saturday night about 1 month ago and the delivery girl was about 25 y.o, Caucasian, medium to heavy build with dyed bright red/burgundy hair and put forth a somewhat dingy smiley demeanor.  I was originally going to tip her $3 and then she said she didn't have change on her and would have to go back to the car.  She said this as she eyeballed my custom made sofa I had purchased in Los Angeles. I told her she could keep it and didn't have to give me any change (leaving her with a $5 tip at this point). Delivery girl then went on to how she got the total wrong (again playing ditsey girl) and the charge was really $5 more.  At this point I was so disgusted I just gave her the money so she would get away before I made a scene in front of my own apartment.  She seemed very skilled at this so I was pretty sure she had done this before and gotten away with  it.  I complained ti the manager and I was granted a $10 credit, which I used. But my issue and the reason I am still writing this review is this:  when I went to pick up my credit order on a Saturday night the Delivery girl who tries to work the customers was still there (I can live with that).  However I noticed that she was carrying on with the manager in a sing song almost flirty manner, and it was Saturday night, one of the busiest and most profitable days for a delivery person to work. It seems she still had her one of the best shifts at her job, even after this incident.  A week later I called to use my remaining credit and mentioned the incident to the person on the phone to which they replied, "Oh yeah, I don't think she's working her anymore."  To which I responded, "Yes she does, I saw her there last week". I had the impression that this person was trying to protect Delivery girl for some reason and my guess is it has something to do with the male manager.  I will say that the brief dynamic I saw between male manager and Delivery girl was a little too comfortable  and familiar for a typical working relationship.  Well, my point is that you have to watch this Delivery girl if she comes to your door. Because from what I saw there is no real or solid reason she has to quit her antics.  She'll still get to keep her profitable Saturday night shift and still be on chummy terms with her boss.</text>

< Text>

Its main stores are Albertsons and Home Depot but it also has a bank, gas station, fast food restaurants etc. The best part is that all the locations order on the borders of the shopping mall which gives you a lot of parking I never really putting your car too far from anyone place.< /Text>

< review>
Rented a truck for 75 minutes from here to pick up a washer machine.  This process was s breeze.  All I needed was my license, proof of insurance  and my credit card. I was charged $50 and then refunded $26 when I returned the truck. I did put about $3 worth of gas in, we didn't drive the truck very far and probably didn't need to put any in but I wasn't getting charged some absurd amount. The gentleman in the tool rental where I got the truck was great, he knew his stuff and was just very courteous.  He made sure i was good driving and set to go.  Renting the truck from Home Depot is super easy!< /review>

< review>
All entrances into this shopping center are off center! You enter from Lomita Blvd and like 20 feet after entering, you have to stop for cross traffic because they don't have a stop. It should be the other way around. The shopping center has good stores. Home Depot, Staples and a supermarket that is very clean and quite large! There are fast food restaurants on the East corner and parking there is very tight and difficult! There's an awkwardly placed gas station and getting in and out of it is like a game of chicken. They need to redesign the parking lot to make stores more easily accessible. It's kind of a rat's maze< /review>
